76561197982480003,Recommended,319480,17237534,"Posted: 26 July, 2015",all,Beepner,"Oniken was a tribute to the... not-so-great linear cyberpunk action platformers in the style of Power Blade or Shatterhand. Developer Joymasher has constructed a much more solid effort in the form of Odallus: The Dark Call, a more exploration focused affair set against a swords and Satanism backdrop. Though the term ""Metroidvania"" is being thrown around with this one, Odallus actually has more in common with the NES Strider game than with pre-SotN Castlevanias. In short, it's what I had hoped Rondo of Blood would be before I learned that Rondo of Blood isn't actually that good.The thing that makes this game click for me is, while the stages are laid in the framework of ""go from point A to point B and fight a boss,"" the areas themselves are actually quite massive and reward a bit of poking around. It follows the motif of being locked off from a certain area before collecting THE THING that opens that area up, but discovering the alternate exits in the stages that lead to their sublevels or just seeing the way the routes loop back on each other is a reward in its own right for exploration nerds. It can get a bit overwhelming at times, the game has no automap and unless you're taking diligent notes, you're going to have a bit of a time remembering where you have and haven't poked around in your search for that last secret in a given stage. However, this approach is a bit more organic and fulfilling than ""color in spots on a map"" and helps extend a rather brief game in a manner that doesn't feel tacked on. I'm not sure exactly how much is required to uncover before you're allowed to make it to the final stage, but we'll probably get a good idea with future speedruns or Games Done Quick events.The game does have some rough edges. While controlling Haggis is responsive enough for the most part, combat can be frustrating given the short reach of your sword and the sometimes dubious hitboxes. If your experience is anything like mine, you're going to end up cheesing the hell out of a boss or two just to keep the game moving. Jumping while attacking is especially wonky, since this is one of those games where jump height is controlled by the duration of the button press. There's sometimes some weird stuff going on with the scrolling, each stage will have arbitrary spots where the screen has to quickly scroll vertically to reveal some area that's off the beaten path. The effect can be disorienting and at times even causes Haggis to jerk around like a catfish on deck. I'm also not sure if some of the grammatical errors in the admittedly over-dramatized dialog are an intentional tribute to the rushed localizations of the 8-bit era, or just natural goofs. They don't show up quite frequently enough to suggest that they are intentional, but they're about the only comic relief in a story that plays it 100% straight.If you prefer your sprites and your gameplay decidedly on the 8-bit portion of the spectrum, definitely give Odallus a shot. Visually, it's a gorgeous game, even at its most grotesque, and it will probably hit the same kinds of buttons that Shovel Knight did for players who grew up in the pre-polygon era. With just a little more polish it could have been a perfect 10, but it's still worth the price of admission."
,Recommended,319480,26355619,"Posted: 1 November, 2016",all,spookydoom,"Recommended if you love NES era games.This is as good of a modern NES game as a Tarantino movie is a citation of all the movies he loves. No matter how many games claim to be a ""modern day NES game that wasn't released in the day"". Usually you can feel that they are not. Some aspects of them are usually too modern in the way they are executed - be it the art or the interface or cetain gameplay aspects. This doesn't make those games bad or anything it's just that they don't match the description.Odallus is different here. It feels 98% like it yould have been released on an NES cardtridge except that a few things would not have been possible on the old hardware (screen sized bosses for example). Otherwise this is a game that channels all the right things from castlevania and the metroid series into one medieval package. Little bits and pieces thrown in from other games as well.Things you might want to know before buying:It has tough parts. Some frustratingly tough parts but nothing in the style of 1001 spikes. Mostly fair tough (except the cart-* rides - you will know what I mean).*  Bosses are pattern learning fights. Get the pattern down - defeat the boss but ...*  ... search your power ups. You will need them.* controlls are very precise and responsiveOverall super cool game. Highly recommended for people who know the type of game they are getting.Otherwise ask people 30+ years old if they can show you what an 8Bit game looks and plays like. ;)One thing that really annoyed me, though:The underwater effect. I assume most players don't mind it that much but it made me really dizzy at times.Unfortunately there are a lot of underwater effect passages - even rather long ones.Otherwise though - loved it. Absolutely recommended."
