76561198028088564,Recommended,319480,17119556,"Posted: 18 July, 2015",all,winnietheshit,"All of the visual style of a NES game with few of the headaches.It's challenging, but not too challenging. As you level your character up, you'll go back to previous levels to find new secrets and unlock new locations which. The levels are well done and don't become tedious. Enemies are tough, but fair. Bosses are fun, and you can tank some of them if you're fast enough. The controls are solid, they don't allow you to overpower the enemies with spamming attacks, so you must plan carefully and be patient.The story is pulpy but mysterious and interesting enough to keep you going.The game seems to have some bugs on some systems. I found that VJOY was interfering with my xbox controller, so I disabled Vjoy. I also found that the game didn't play well with Steam overlay on, so I disabled that as well. Since doing those minor work arounds, the game has performed perfectly. The developer also seems responsive to issues and releases regular patches.Good Game."
76561198024378091,Not Recommended,319480,26141004,"Posted: 20 October, 2016",all,minstrelofmoria,"Superficially the Castlevania to Axiom Verge's Metroid, but far more slavishly devoted to even the worst concepts from ancient platformers. Were you somehow nostalgic for mine cart levels? Here's an obnoxiously long one with a frustrating boss at the end who'll keep running out your lives and forcing you to redo the whole thing! Did you love struggling with ice and wind? Have both in the same level, along with projectile-using enemies whose shots are hard enough to dodge already! Wonky hitboxes and sparse healing add to the frustration, and the paucity of useful goodies in each level makes the inevitable health loss from exploring feel like a punishment rather than a test of skill.I decided that whether I finished the game would determine whether I gave it a thumbs up or a thumbs down. I think I was at somewhere around the halfway point when I called it quits. I'd much rather play something like Shovel Knight or even Hyper Light Drifter that pays homage while still playing fair."
,Recommended,319480,28550892,"Posted: 22 December, 2016",all,Vookatos,"If you're looking for something that would remind you of Castlevania, look no further. Odallus is a pretty good platformer that takes inspiration from the famous classic horror series, but still stands on its own.It plays like older NES games, even going as far as to include life counter, yet with the inclusion of the world map, it also offers a Metroidvania experience. First and foremost, however, it's still a platformer. Just with a couple of side-paths and power ups. Don't expect it to rival actual Metroidvania games in that aspect.I should probably mention right away that lives won't bother you much. There are shortcuts that you activate within levels that will always stay open, and Game Overs only put you back to the beginning of the level/world map. It's definitely one of the less-obtrusive live systems in any game.The gameplay and controls are tight, and, thankfully, also don't emulate worst part of older games. You're always in control, and if you fall down a pit, it's always your fault.Level design is not bad, but there are a few annoying gimmicks along the way. They're all really small, and Metroidvania aspect helps with that a lot. For example, there is one really annoying boss that comes to mind, but you can open up a level where you can get a Level 3 sword before fighting him, and make him a non-issue.The game's relatively easy if you've played many platformers, but it will provide enough challenge to keep you entertained. Took me about 6 hours to beat, and that's just the normal difficulty setting. There's also a harder one, which promises new item placements, among other things, but from what I've seen, it's quite annoying. The first level had randomly spawning enemies on bosses, which isn't a good sign.One thing that felt weird was the shop system. Throughout the game you find shops where you can buy weapon ammo, lives and health items. Once you buy any of the items, the price for that item rises. Considering that sometimes you need items to solve puzzles, it's a weird decision. If you're not good at the game and, for example, keep losing to a boss, I can see it leading to grinding money, which is just bad. Consider this your PSA: do not buy items unless absolutely needed. Restocking on, say, 2 axes you've wasted on every opportunity to do so will probably lead to grinding.The only thing that I really didn't enjoy were a LOT of bugs I encountered. One boss' attack was broken, text box that displayed lines of code, what seemed to be broken AI in some places, and plethora of smaller issues that weren't really major, but definitely annoyed me. Still, nothing gamebreaking.In short, if you're looking for a pretty good retro platformer with a great atmosphere, get it."
,Recommended,319480,34001500,Posted: 3 August,all,Graham von Poopenswine,"Rating: 9.5/10Odallus is a story-driven platformer which pays homage the NES-era of Castlevania titles. JoyMasher builds upon the success of their last game, Oniken, and brings a level of much desired polish. It's not often you find a truly amazing throwback game such as Odallus here on Steam; however, this title definently defines everything desireable in a story-driven Metroidvania game!I found there were things I both liked, and disliked, about Odallus; however, there were far more that I liked than disliked. Here are a few you should be aware of before buying:+ Odallus sports an immersive story, it has a fully animated cinematic seen before you even reach the titlescreen, as well as a cutscene before you start the first level of the game. Each boss has ample dialog to keep the player entertained.+ The player character has nice and fluid, tight controls.+ Much like any Castlevania title, this game has a weapon system similar to Castlevania where you find weapons that act similar to powerups.+ Weapon usage is no longer convoluted and is bound to a single key, I'm looking at you Oniken.+ Checkpoints!+ Enemies drop currency which can be used at shops which are often located at points of interest in each level.+ Branching paths in the level design offer rewards for exploration.- Odallus, similar to JoyMasher's first game ""Oniken"", launches in their own launcher. This launcher offers features that should be handled in the in-game main menu."
