76561198040295426,Recommended,319480,32737012,Posted: 24 June,all,diegzumillo,"Very good game in all aspects. Levels are big and fun to explore. There is a very light metroid element to it, where you can collect new powers and revisit old areas.It is, however, an old school game. It's not just the art style and basic mechanics, it's old school all the way. I personally find that a bit of a turn off, because we learned a lot about designing games in the last 30 years and a lot of common tropes back didn't age well in  my opinion. But I'm not judging the designer's choice here; there is an audience for this, for sure.It's not as hard as other old school games. But enough to trigger a few rage quits, which for me is a problem; that's not the kind of experience I like in a game. I've had my fair share of those already.I also have  a problem with the dash, an ability you find later on the game. The dash is triggered by double tapping the d-pad, like it used to be on many old games. If I didn't have more buttons on my controller/keyboard  I would take that as non-ideal but acceptable solution, but I do have more buttons. And ever since I got that ability I keep throwing myself at danger accidentally, because this is a platformer that requires a very agile dpad control! So I tap it constantly to adjust my trajectory and position. You can see how that's a problem. Then, of course, just to make me more frustrated, whenever I'm in an urgent situation and need to dash quickly, it doesn't work. Because of course not.I do wish I'd see more games looking at the past for inspiration. There are many interesting things games used to do that is almost lost today. But I'd rather see some experimentation on top of that as well, rather than direct transposition just for nostalgia sake.If direct transposition for nostalgia sake is what you're looking for, look no further. If this game were released 20 years ago it would have been my favorite game."
