76561198185291783,Recommended,319480,29033628,Posted: 5 January,all,henrodsantos,"Tech: The game runs smoothly and with very few noticeble bugs. Framerate is stable and there are not any graphical glitches,Aesthetics: The art direction is gorgeous. Both levels and sprites emulate the late NES konami/capcom era very well. The game does takes some liberties, but they end up being for the better.Sound: The soundtrack itself is average, but it gets the job done. Sound effects are more similar to what you would expect to hear from a megadrive, but that it is not detrimental for the game in any way.Gameplay: It feels very similar to a pre-metroidvania Castlevania, specially Rondo of Blood. You have the sword as your main weapon and your secondary weapons that must be replenished. The game have a few metroidvania elements though, as backtracking is necessary in some points in order to find acessories that will allow you to continue your progress. I do feel the B levels would benefit from being interconnected, but I see what the developers were going for.Story: The game preaches the principle ""show don't tell"", which is just great! The flow of the game is very tight and as you explore the world you start to uncover the lore and the mysteries behind the odallus and the old Gods. If you don't' care about the story at all, there is no problem either: It is possible to just ignore it altogether. Dialog can be a bit clunky or have some questionable choices though, but nothing that compromises the experience."
