76561198037917342,Recommended,319480,22307664,"Posted: 8 April, 2016",all,「SUPER EUROBEAT」,"A worthy successor to the action platformers of old, Odallus does pretty much everything right.tl;dr:Game is great. Combat is precise and rewards thoughtful play. Areas are well designed. Backtracking is well designed such that you always get rewarded for your trouble. Difficulty increases steadily throughout the game. Platforming is not cheap and punishing, but is instead a lot of fun. The setting and plot of the game is reminiscent of Berserk. If you like Symphony of the Night or Mega Man X you will be right at home here.In-depth review:The thing that really struck me about this game is that it is one of the fairest games I've ever played. Most other ""retro"" games nowadays bombard you with cheap deaths and ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥t enemies, but not this game. Every enemy and obstacle in the game can be overcome with precise timing, tactics, and spacing. Every enemy has an attack pattern that it will follow, which is what you as the player need to analyze and overcome. One or two ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥tty enemies aside, everything in this game fits that mold. Platforming sections are much of the same. Once you figure out what sequence of button presses you need, you can do it perfectly every time. If you can't figure out how to do it with just your sword, there are 3 sub-weapons available to help you. These sub-weapons are ranged attacks with different trajectories, similar to the knife, axe, and holy water in Castlevania.The other thing that really delighted me was the strict adherence to the action part of the action platformer genre. The difference between an action platformer and a regular platformer is the focus on combat. No instant death pits, no knockback when you get hit, no pixel perfect jumps, etc. Though the game has a lot of platforming sections, most of them are pretty easy and straightforward. It is the combat with enemies that will wear you down. A really cool feature of this game is the ability to parry enemy projectiles by hitting them with your sword. This allows you to stay on the offensive much more than you normally would be able to because now instead of jumping all around to dodge stuff, you can stay right up in your enemies face and block all his stuff while hitting him at the same time. This adds another layer of skill to the game, as well as forcing the player to think about the risk/reward of blocking projectiles. As I mentioned above though, enemies obey strict timings in their attacks, which you can master. In the end you feel like a badass while also feeling challenged.The last part of the game I want to talk about is the exploration and the secrets. It's really good. The game has a very open and vertical layout, more similar to Wizards and Warriors than to any Castlevania game. The game follows the same general formula as every metroidvania games. You will see a part of a level that is unreachable to you, making you say to yourself ""oh, there must be an item that lets me get that"". However, the item progression is very much non-linear in the sense that you will not get the double jump item right after you encounter you first jump that requires it. Most items like that are buried deep at the end of a labyrinth, usually requiring you to traverse a large area while hitting a bunch of switches that will lower a gate with an item behind it. The first time this happened I had no idea what to expect, each time you get an item (save for one instance) it is a complete surprise. This is a nice break from the scenario I described above where you can pretty much perfectly predict when you will get a certain item.The reason the exploration aspect of the game is so good is becaue of the level design and layout. The level progression is basically taken straight from Castlevania 3. Every level has two exits, one that will take you to the next main level, and one ""secret"" exit that will take you to a different level. The levels aren't really secret as they are required to finish the game, but I'm going to call them by that name. I noticed that the secret levels have a higher difficulty level than the main ones, which is a nice touch because the game is designed such that you access those levels later in the game. What basically ends up happening is that you find an item in a main level, then go back through every previous level and secret level until you find a spot where you can get somewhere you couldn't before. This will often lead to another new item that will let you reach other new areas in other levels. This cycle continues until you have every item, but also gets more difficult as the later secret levels are quite a bit more difficult than the main levels. The game also tells you how many items there are to collect in each level so you don't to crazy trying to keep track, a much appreciated touch.Of couse the game is not perfect so here I will talk about the stuff that I didn't like or stuff that could be improved on. The shops in the game suffer from severe Skyrim syndrome. What I mean is that they are nice to have in the beginning of the game and can be quite useful, but by the end you will be skipping every one becuase you never have the need to buy anything. In addition to this, your gold total is ever increasing with nothing to spend it on. This isn't really a problem as much as a nitpick, but I went in expecting at least something important to be available in the shop, but the only things to buy a healing items, sub-weapon ammo, and extra lives. Nothing new is ever added.The other thing I don't think is quite perfect is the bosses. The games combat is set up in such a way that once you figure out the bosses pattern, it becomes trivial to defeat. This is fine for regular enemies, but I would have liked to see some of the bosses with a rage mode that changed up attack timings and added new attacks. I also think some of the bosses could have done with some more health, I was able to kill some of them after just a few attacks. On the flip side though, this game has some incredibly creative and original bosses, which I love to see. At the end of the day though, defeating the bosses didn't really fill me with satisfaction as much as it filled me with the feeling that I had just completed a chore.Overall the game is fantastic and is the best retro style game I've played since they became a thing, even beating out Shovel Knight and Axiom Verge. I got it on sale but it's absolutely worth the full price."
,Recommended,319480,18820913,"Posted: 1 November, 2015",all,zehelvion,"So yeah, I decided to write a review. I've probably never done this before.tl;dr:The game is cool and it does feel like an oldskul title.Graphics:The graphics are sometimes obviously much better (as they benefit hardware wise), using capabilities that were not available back in the day.Their blend of pixel-art-style is unique and somewhat strange as they intentionally used very few colors for every character and creature in the game (less than you normally would expect from an actual 8-bit title). Unlike an actual 8-bit title, the sprites don't share colors often. Each sprite has it's own set of colors and each color-set is somewhat distinct and specific to a single sprite. This makes for a very crisp and clear display that also stirs some strange emotions at times. There was something very alien at times about the graphical choices in old games and I think this bizarre use of (very few) colors captures that very well and even builds up on this making for a very unique vibe that somehow melds in my mind with 80's and early 90's Heavy Metal albums.The intro animation is pretty fantastic.Gameplay:The gameplay is rather good. It is very enjoyable with a joypad. I'd imagine that without one (using the keyboard), it would not be so much fun probably. You constantly feel like you are freshening up on your action platformer skills. You will improve if you play carefully and pay attention to patterns, doing what you can to learn from your mistakes.Exploring the game is fun and it is vast so there is plenty to explore for a few hours.The weapon and armor upgrades feel right and the secrets are fun and rewarding to look for.Challenge:The difficulty in this game could be vastly mitigated by the weapons, armor and hearts you find along the way, as well as the shops that are simply a play to grab additional health and ammo.Some enemies are harder to figure out than others. Some enemies are fairly easy once you understand their patterns.The game isn't hard but it's also rarely too easy (although that does happen). This is subjective. Some people find it too hard and I feel there are areas in the game that are more challenging than others. Overall there are no annoying spikes.Story:The story is a pretty simple plot about Dark Gods, evil demons and a lone superiorly skilled soldier made demon hunter going around, searching and slaying more and more evil creatures that happen upon his path. The texts are pretty good and fit with the atmosphere of the game.Sound:The sound effects and the music are good, I've never felt the urge to listen to music in the BG when I'm playing this game even though I imagine that Heavy Metal would suit this wonderfully.Overall:* Do you like Metroidvania games?* Do you prefer a gritty dark atmosphere in games?* Do you like the aesthetics of old games like Golden Axe and Rastan?If you answered yes, there's a good chance you""ll love (or like) this game.It is pretty good. Don't think there is any other game on Steam that really scratches that itch. Well actually there is! Axiom Verge I believe but the two games are very different. If you are into this sort of thing you""ll probably end up playing both of them if that's within your time constraints."
