,Recommended,319480,22582066,"Posted: 23 April, 2016",all,Hao | Shameless Seamus,"This is an excellent retro platform adventure game.  It draws inspiration from many games during the NES era, while integrating some modern mechanics to keep things interesting.  Initially the homage to the first three Castlevanias is very apparent, the graphics, level select and movement all bring back a familiarity that even later Castlevania's have trouble envoking. The level design and game mechanics also pay homage to many other franchises from that era as well.Progressing through the levels I found areas that reminded me of jumping through the tree tops in Wizards and Warriors, a mythology and backdrop as rich as The Battle of Olympus and plenty of secret areas initially unaccessable which would require me to return with specific relics that allow me to perform great feats much like a Zelda game.Then there are the bosses fights.  These delightful bouts with demon knights and giant monsters will seem familar to anyone who has played Castlevania or Metroid but the boss fights also draw influence from modern games such as Dark Souls.  The patterns for some of the bosses are incredibly complex, drawing the perfect amount of anxiety between each move. I'd fumble and die many times before learning their entire cycle.  By the end I'm ducking and hanging off of edges, jumping and cleaving all in perfect sync creating some of the most fluid and dance like boss battles I've witnessed in a game.This game has a lot of depth to it, and despite borrowing heavily from so many classic games, once the rose coloured glasses associated with the nostaligia it invoked wore off it is a well polished and interesting game that holds it's own weight.  The player has lots of control over the character, you can climb ledges and move blocks, trade with merchants, or find relics to add some extra abilities.  Each level drawing from a different inspiration presents a smörgåsbord of playgrounds to explore each one unique in its play style while all keeping the same familar control."
