76561198022657661,Recommended,319480,27383097,"Posted: 24 November, 2016",all,Harrison Ford,"It's been a long time since I've beaten a modern game and read the words, ""Thank you for playing!"" at the very end.I can't say enough good things about Odallus: The Dark Call.  It's well written (minus a few minor typos) and has tight controls and is very challenging.  Odallus is an excellent action side scrolling action game that reminded me of many games of old: Ninja Gaiden, Mega Man X, Metroid, Castlevania, Magician Lord, Super Ghouls 'n Ghosts, Demon's Crest, Donkey Kong Country,  and Xardion, to name a few.The reason I love Odallus so much, is even how familiar it felt it was full of great surprises.  Many of the power ups surprised and delighted me.  They felt like familiar friends, all coming together to hang out.  Given the style of game that it is, Odallus uses it's power ups in nice, game changing ways.  Sure, they increase your accessability, but they also make you think in new ways and give you new approaches in combat, which by the way, is very tight.Many of the enemies behaved in ways that I didn't expect.  I would often look at enemies and think of something it reminded me of from another game...and then it would do something completely different and force me to react in a new way.  It was like a new twist on something old, and I play a lot of old games from the NES and SNES era so this game was highly relatable for me.  Some things were rote;  for example, there's the enemy that flies in odd patterns, then glides across the screen and drops fireballs on you.  I literally just fought something like that in Demon's Crest yesterday, yet, this boss felt fresh due to the way the developers used the terrain and some other mix up attacks.  Definitely my favorite boss fight.  (I won't say what level it was in so you don't get spoiled.)I played the game on a wireless Xbox 360 controller, and it worked great.  The controls are simple and make sense.  I did not try keyboard controls.If I had to say one bad thing about the game, it's that two of the areas are far, far too large and were frustrating to navigate because they were too easy to get lost in.  In the case of those two levels, I would say to the devs, ""Less is more,"" and especially for a game like this.  I finished my first playthrough in under 5 hours, and it was a very fun ride.  The progression felt great, and finding all the secrets really made me think.I feel that the game is underpriced.  I think $10.00 would be more than reasonable for a game like this, considering that it has a lot of replayability.  I can't wait to play through the game again and try a different sequence of events.The music in the game is great, just as an extra mention, as are the sound effects.  Very classy and enjoyable.As for level design, this game nails so many grand and subtle design choices that it felt like I was playing a modern summary of older video games.  So many times I found myself saying, ""Oh, that reminds me of NInja Gaiden, or Mega Man X!""  Even though this game borrows mechanics from many other games, it definitely feels like it has it's own personality and can easily stand on it's own feet.  The bosses are very well designed, although a couple of them felt trivial because I could just button mash them.Overall, I rate this game a 9/10, giving it a ding for those extra large levels, which frustrated me.This game is an easy recommendation for people who like action and exploration with power ups that increase your accessability as you go.  I hope many people get an opportunity to enjoy it, because it might make younger gamers try older games, and it will definitely make older games remember ""the old days."""
