76561198119880452,Not Recommended,319480,20795090,"Posted: 27 January, 2016",all,Daimoth,"Don't let the Demon's Crest name drop fool you, this is 8-bit difficulty at its most fickle, which pairs poorly with an old school lives system. Though to its credit, you aren't forced to enter a lengthy password afterward.The controlls are only marginally less stiff than those of the 8-bit Castlevania games, from which this Odallus is primarily derived. Seriously, do not play this game if you don't like the way the old Castlevania games handled. You even fly backward when you take damage. And yes, there will be water hazards.Odallus is in need of a quality-of-life patch. I found a menu which can only be exited by scrolling to the bottom of a list, the stage select and ""begin stage"" functionalities are accessed separately; all things which would have been mildly grating even in the '80s. And to the horror of the TotalBiscuits of the world, the options menu is sparse, and only accessible before the game actually launches.Technical problems and bugs: Odallus is picky about controllers. I ended up using an old SNES controller piped through a USB adapter. If you die during a boss fight, you'll occasionally end up with both the boss music and the stage music playing simultaneously. And after the second boss fight, I had to faff around to get the game to accept character input again - I found entering and exiting the start menu worked most reliably. It's worth noting that I began playing in windowed mode after suspecting the game didn't handle alt+tabbing well - some of these bugs may be attributable to that.I appreciate what they were trying to do - believe me, I do - but this one's a bit low on playability."
