76561198161628677,Recommended,319480,29043669,Posted: 5 January,all,lastride,"Odallus is a Metroidvania action platformer that borrows a lot of gameplay aspects from the NES classics such as Castlevania, Metroid and Zelda II.  And where so many indie games have failed, Odallus does a decent job of carrying the old formula and at the same time feeling like bringing something new on the table.You play as Haggis, en Ex Soldier and now a hunter who has lost his wife.The war is over and now he lives a peaceful life with his son. One night when he left the village to go for hunting demonic-like creatures evaded his village and kidnapped his son. Now he is set on to find his son back and take revenge for pillaging his village.The graphics are 8 bit style and it is so NES alike they even went with a NES color pallet. You are presented the story through dialog and through some artifacts that you discover throughout the game. The background graphics however are more detailed and look more 16 bit. Personally I would prefer it, if they had made a 16 bit design but I understand what the developer was aiming for. The music is decent, -more on the depressing side, which I think fits the serious tone of the game. Everything else that evolves presentation is simplistic, like the Map, the inventory, the dialogs etc.The gameplay will be familiar to those who have played retro action platformers. While it is very simplistic it takes some time to get used to the controls etc. There are the classic mechanics - most of them you acquire as upgrades as you progress- like double jumping, dashing, secondary attacks, armor upgrades and more. The game overall might not offer a lot of replay ability since it is very straightforward but it gets very addicting when you start getting the achievements.Some things I didn’t like are first of all difference in difficulty in some areas. It gets really hard in some stages and a piece of cake in others. Also the bosses are very creative from a design perspective but you can beat most of them by just taking the damage and spam attack their weak points. The last boss however is one of the hardest ones I have ever played and a very memorable in my opinion. Some other minor things like the attempt to make funny dialog while the game is super serious doesn’t make sense as well.All in all, I really enjoyed my time with Odallus, the exploration, the tight controls, the overall dark theme and the hunt for achievements make an addicting package that anyone who likes those types of games should give it a shot. Some go as far as calling it a hidden gem and I don’t disagree at all with that statement."
